    "body_en": "<p>Listen to this audio excerpt from Erik Richards, Near Space Network Mission Manager: For Erik Richards, supporting NASA’s first crewed Artemis mission to the Moon and back is the culmination of a career spent helping spacecraft communicate with Earth. Like many kids who grew up at the height of the Space Shuttle…</p><p>In astronomy, a result matters for more than the headline. What counts is whether it sharpens the physical reconstruction of the observed system, constrains models and adds context for future measurements.</p><h2>What the story actually shows</h2><p>From the source material credited to NASA, the most useful details are these: Listen to this audio excerpt from Erik Richards, Near Space Network Mission Manager. For Erik Richards, supporting NASA’s first crewed Artemis mission to the Moon and back is the culmination of a career spent helping spacecraft communicate with Earth. Read without publicity varnish, that is the part that helps separate what was directly observed, measured or calculated from what is still interpretation.</p><p>Institutional releases are useful starting points, but they naturally foreground the headline result. Mature science reporting has to preserve room for caveats, uncertainty ranges and competing interpretations.</p><blockquote>In science reporting, the useful part is not the excitement. It is the evidence that remains standing after the excitement has passed.</blockquote><h2>What to watch next</h2><p>The next meaningful step is usually to combine this result with new observations, ideally at other wavelengths, to test whether the picture remains consistent. That is the standard needed before a finding associated with NASA deserves to be treated as settled rather than merely exciting.</p>",
