    "body_en": "<p>An invisible companion consuming material from the naked-eye star gamma-Cas has been revealed as the culprit for curious X-rays coming from the stellar system. This closes the case on a mystery that has puzzled astronomers for more than fifty years.</p><p>In astronomy, a result matters for more than the headline. What counts is whether it sharpens the physical reconstruction of the observed system, constrains models and adds context for future measurements.</p><h2>What the story actually shows</h2><p>From the source material credited to ESA Space Science, the most useful details are these: An invisible companion consuming material from the naked-eye star gamma-Cas has been revealed as the culprit for curious X-rays coming from the stellar system. This closes the case on a mystery that has puzzled astronomers for more than fifty years. Read without publicity varnish, that is the part that helps separate what was directly observed, measured or calculated from what is still interpretation.</p><p>Institutional releases are useful starting points, but they naturally foreground the headline result. Mature science reporting has to preserve room for caveats, uncertainty ranges and competing interpretations.</p><blockquote>In science reporting, the useful part is not the excitement. It is the evidence that remains standing after the excitement has passed.</blockquote><h2>What to watch next</h2><p>The next meaningful step is usually to combine this result with new observations, ideally at other wavelengths, to test whether the picture remains consistent. That is the standard needed before a finding associated with ESA Space Science deserves to be treated as settled rather than merely exciting.</p>",
